Change-Id: I4736d112b004c4356731de8a37d97fc6536793db

Add root_helper to quantum agents.

When running commands that require root privileges, the linuxbridge,
openvswitch, and ryu agent now prepend the commands with the value of
the root_helper config variable. This is set to "sudo" in the plugins'
.ini files, allowing the agent to run as a non-root user with
appropriate sudo privilidges.

If root_helper is changed to "sudo quantum-rootwrap",
then the command being run will be filtered against lists of each
agent's valid commands in quantum/rootwrap. See
http://wiki.openstack.org/Packager/Rootwrap for details.

Fixes bug 948467.

payload.head: 30b583195e4c7938dec4a84faa26a218a65d4054
shas:
Add player that avoids getting chosen as a target.

The basic idea is that most players have code that looks like this:

    others = Game.world[:players].select { |p| p != self }

This player just defines == so that it's always true for any
PlayerProxy, and so players pretty much skip over it. :) A more
cheatproof way is to compare #object_id, as that way you're not giving
the PlayerProxy object any arguments to play with, so it doesn't know
who is looking at it.

Other than that, it's a pretty braindead attack-the-weakest-guy bot.

Last is a bunch of misc fixes found trying to get ARMED! running on iOS and WinRT.

Improvements to database replication.

Note: I'd like to get this released as soon as possible as it is a
data durability issue.

1) Orders nodes so that none get starved (see code and footnote).

2) New max_diffs setting that caps how long the replicator will spend
   trying to sync a given database per pass so the other databases
   don't get starved.

3) Replaces run_pause with the more standard "interval", which means
   the replicator won't pause unless it takes less than the interval
   set.

Change-Id: I986742229e65031df88f5251ca61746b7c8d2bde
Merge "Change account pending to behave like container..."

Remove old stats tools.

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/swift/+spec/remove-old-swift-stats-tools

Change-Id: Ibb57b3d71c7f18060d2d48a1d3754a7f1444624d

Refactor partition gathering.

RingBuilder._reassign_parts() is really moving one (partition,
replica) pair at a time. However, the way that _gather_reassign_parts
passes that data in was strange; it would update each replica's entry
in _replica2part2dev to 0xffff, then return a list of affected
partitions. Now it just returns the pairs to move.

This is helpful in the presence of bugs that affect partition
assignment (e.g. #943493), there's no chance of stray 0xffff values
hanging around and corrupting the partition map.

Also, update my email address.

Change-Id: Ifb3aeb4fac750f66e2ddbad88eb5846e72bac20c

Return NoSuchBucket/Key on 404.

- Fixes bug 945937.

Change-Id: If6dd53a716491a7d1a9ab4992224038ede4cb32a

Create tmpfile in the same dir as the cache file

Make sure we don't try to rename files across devices. Fixes bug 949366

Change-Id: I75581a0682c8db90cad9b077b1c22a886d234e31

Add support for venv-based test run with tox.

 * Adds tox config
   - based on the config from python-quantumclient and updated for
     test, pep8 and coverage execution as per nova's run_tests.sh.
 * Adds nosetests defaults in setup.cfg
 * Adds runtime dependencies in tools/pip-requires
   - dependencies were gathered by referencing the packages used in
     creation of a Swift All In One.  Versions were determined by
     checking the swift-core/trunk ppa or, failing that, the version
     available in lucid.
 * Adds test dependencies in tools/test-requires
 * Updates swift/common/middleware/formpost.py for pep8 compliance
 * Adds instructions for executing the tests with Tox to the
   developer_guidelines
 * Adds instructions for installing openstack.nose_plugin to
   developer_saio
 * Fixes bug 909177

payload.head: d2ee139db94f1edb0510b2e5b72a3c3014dcb4ea
shas:
Handle post-review from a detached HEAD using git

When running from a detached HEAD (not on a branch), post-review fails after a
call to git symbolic-ref.
[nmorey@sat:db ((f8dcfa9...) $)]$ post-review --guess-summary
--guess-description --parent=HEAD~1
Failed to execute command: ['git', 'symbolic-ref', '-q', 'HEAD']

However we do not need to be on a branch to have the script working.
So this patch ignores errors from git symbolic-ref and add tests for
self.head_ref being not set.

Reviewed at http://reviews.reviewboard.org/r/2985/

pull_request.body:
Ref: http://open.silverstripe.org/ticket/6175

Can you review this please and let me know if this is helpful? 

I've attempted to clean up the multitude of the caches on the DataObject, and make them at least more consistent and more visible - although I didn't try to merge them or refactor the code to eliminate them.

Have also explicitly deprecated setComponent - it manipulates "componentCache" which to my eye is no longer used anywhere, and can cause some hidden surprises for people out there. Fixed related CsvBulkLoader problem which was still using setComponent.

Removed $cache_buildSQL_query, which was not used.

Fixed DataObject::reset to clean all global caches, and DataObject::flushCache to flush the component cache. Both now are doing what it says on the box.

The problem reported in ticket 6175 can now be fixed by doing $this->flushCache(); after the setting the has_one and writing.

Comments welcome :)
pull_request.title: Re: has_one component cache can't be cleared.

pull_request.body:
This pull gives full coverage of all the printing methods in the physics.quantum module, inspired as the first step in @Krastanov 's old pull #186 to rework the printing in the quantum module.

This first commit implements tests for all printing methods in the quantum module, which I checked with the coverage report. No changes are made to the printing methods, this is just to establish a baseline for verifying valid output capable of working in the ipython Qt console and html notebook. Note XFAIL tests show where there are errors in the printing methods.

Also in this pull is a fix for latex printing of AntiCommutator, which would give an invalid latex expression which would not display in either the Qt console or html notebook. The current implementation gives valid latex output which displays in the ipython html notebook, but I could not get the ipython Qt console to output the curly brackets.

I have a few decently large nested expressions which can display alright in the html notebook, but I may gradually add some depending on when this is merged and how much free time I get. Any suggestions on these would be greatly appreciated.

I have a ipynb file that can be run to see the output from everything in the new tests rendered by the html notebook and a py script that does the same for the qtconsole. Note that the py script is not a normal example, as has function calls to display in the IPython environment when executed with ``%run`` magic.

payload.head: bf1131cc50d1295b7c4eb3fce8e23bc17f63c87e
shas: [process] Added destructor to process to make sure handles are always closed in the right order.

[Security][ACL] Fixed ObjectIdentity::fromDomainObject and UserSecurityIdentity::from(Account|Token) when working with proxies

Backported ClassUtils class from Doctrine Common 2.2
Fixes #2611, #2056, #2048, #2035
[Routing] remove duplicated cache of compiled routes

merged branch jalliot/acl_proxies-2 (PR #3826)

Commits
-------

6483d88 [Security][ACL] Fixed ObjectIdentity::fromDomainObject and UserSecurityIdentity::from(Account|Token) when working with proxies

Discussion
----------

[WIP] Fixed ACL handling of Doctrine proxies

Bug fix: yes
Feature addition: no
Backwards compatibility break: no
Symfony2 tests pass: [![Build Status](https://secure.travis-ci.org/jalliot/symfony.png?branch=acl_proxies-2)](http://travis-ci.org/jalliot/symfony)
Fixes the following tickets: #3818, #2611, #2056, #2048, #2035 and probably others
Todo: Fix tests, update changelog

Hi,

As per @fabpot's request, here is #3818 ported to `master`.

> Here is a new attempt to fix all the issues related to Symfony ACL identities and Doctrine proxies.
> It only fixes the issue for Doctrine >=2.2 (older versions of Doctrine will still not work properly with ACL because `Doctrine\Common\Util\ClassUtils` didn't exist before and proxy naming strategy was not consistent between all Doctrine implementations (ORM/ODM/etc.)).

/cc @schmittjoh @beberlei

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by schmittjoh at 2012-04-09T00:07:52Z

I'm -1 on adding a dependency on the Doctrine class.

The naming scheme was designed in a generic way, we should just copy the method.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by jalliot at 2012-04-09T00:13:07Z

@schmittjoh The ACL component requires Doctrine DBAL already (and as such Common) so I don't think this is really an issue at the moment. If (when?) the component is refactored to be decoupled from Doctrine, then maybe we will have to change that.
But I can also copy the class (where?) if you think it is better :)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by schmittjoh at 2012-04-09T01:01:27Z

I'd suggest ``Symfony\Component\Security\Core\Util\ClassUtils``.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by jalliot at 2012-04-09T11:16:19Z

@fabpot @schmittjoh It's done: I've backported the ClassUtils class and its tests from Doctrine Common into the Security component. Maybe this PR can be merged into 2.0 as well now, what do you think?

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by oscherler at 2012-04-11T06:27:20Z

There seems to be a consensus that ACLs don’t (fully?) work with Doctrine < 2.2, i.e. in Symfony 2.0. Can it therefore be documented somewhere, typically on the main documentation page on the subject? http://symfony.com/doc/current/cookbook/security/acl.html

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by jalliot at 2012-04-11T07:36:25Z

@oscherler You can make ACL work with Doctrine < 2.2 and without this patch if you use something like this code (note this is for ORM only but it can be adapted for ODM; it also assumes that your identifier can be retrieved with `getId()`):

``` php
<?php

use Doctrine\ORM\Proxy\Proxy;
use Symfony\Component\Acl\Domain\ObjectIdentity;

$domainObject = ... // some Doctrine entity (maybe a proxy...)

if ($domainObject instanceof Proxy) {
    $objectIdentity = new ObjectIdentity($domainObject->getId(), get_parent_class($domainObject));
} else {
    $objectIdentity = new ObjectIdentity($domainObject->getId(), get_class($domainObject));
}
```
It is ugly but it is the only way to get the correct identity for < 2.2. Never use `ObjectIdentity::fromDomainObject` with a proxy and without this patch!
The same applies to `UserSecurityIdentity`.

This should indeed be documented in the doc for 2.0. /cc @weaverryan

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by jalliot at 2012-04-11T22:34:37Z

I just fixed the tests and squashed the commits.
I didn't write a test for `UserSecurityIdentity::fromAccount` and `fromToken` because I didn't really have time to look for a clean solution (without creating a full UserInterface implementation for instance...). Anyway the test for `ObjectIdentity::fromDomainObject` should be enough I guess...
Don't hesitate to add one if you think it is necessary. /cc @schmittjoh

@fabpot Apart from @beberlei approval to use MIT license, I think it is ready for merge.

payload.head: 0e3d0f3d960bf5b895adcf9ffc79d2077f1411d5
shas:
Input: da9052 - fix memory leak in da9052_onkey_probe()

If, in drivers/input/misc/da9052_onkey.c::da9052_onkey_probe(), the
call to either kzalloc() or input_allocate_device() fails then we will
return -ENOMEM from the function without freeing the other allocation
that may have succeeded, thus we leak either the memory allocated for
'onkey' or the memory allocated for 'input_dev' if one succeeds and
the other fails.
Fix that by jumping to the 'err_free_mem' label at the end of the
function that properly cleans up rather than returning directly.

Signed-off-by: Jesper Juhl <jj@chaosbits.net>
Signed-off-by: Dmitry Torokhov <dtor@mail.ru>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: (no-up) hostap: Change initial operation mode to managed (infra)

This was previously changed by using an "options" line in a modprobe.d
file, however that practice is now deprecated.  This is because module
names, option names, their values and even their current defaults can
all change inside the kernel and module-init-tools has never been kept
in sync.

In addition, changing the kernel means that the option change will apply
if the module is built in by users or the OEM team.

Signed-off-by: Scott James Remnant <scott@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Tim Gardner <tim.gardner@canonical.com>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: (no-up) nbd: Change default partitions per device to 15

This was previously changed by using an "options" line in a modprobe.d
file, however that practice is now deprecated.  This is because module
names, option names, their values and even their current defaults can
all change inside the kernel and module-init-tools has never been kept
in sync.

In addition, changing the kernel means that the option change will apply
if the module is built in by users or the OEM team.

Bug: #342563

Signed-off-by: Scott James Remnant <scott@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Tim Gardner <tim.gardner@canonical.com>

Bug: #330259

Add model specific quirks for the hotkeys for the laptops below:

	Zepto Znote 6615WD
	Zepto Znote 6625WD
	FUJITSU SIEMENS AMILO Xi 2428

In each case the volume keys and the mute key do not correctly produce
key release events.  Quirk these to force a key release. (Patch modified
to compile with 2.6.30)

commit below:

    commit 000c2a35b8b0485f5a872c24c4f2d0d6579951c1

UBUNTU: SAUCE: (no-up) Sony laptop: Some Sony Vaia laptops do not enable wwan power by default.

for the original diatribe.

Signed-off-by: Tim Gardner <tim.gardner@canonical.com>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: (no-up) trace: add trace events for open(), exec() and uselib()

BugLink: http://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/462111

This patch uses TRACE_EVENT to add tracepoints for the open(),
exec() and uselib() syscalls so that ureadahead can cheaply trace
the boot sequence to determine what to read to speed up the next.

It's not upstream because it will need to be rebased onto the syscall
trace events whenever that gets merged, and is a stop-gap.

Signed-off-by: Scott James Remnant <scott@ubuntu.com>
Acked-by: Stefan Bader <stefan.bader@canonical.com>
Acked-by: Andy Whitcroft <andy.whitcroft@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Stefan Bader <stefan.bader@canonical.com>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: (no-up) set /proc/acpi/video/*/DOS to 4 by default

BugLink: http://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/458982

acpi_video_bus_start_devices() in drivers/acpi/video.c sets the default
ACPI DOS value to 0, which lets the OS handle toggling of display output
but still leaves the BIOS handling brightness levels automatically when
connecting/disconnecting AC.

We want the OS to handle both where possible, so a better default would
be to set this to 4.

This likely will regress systems using proprietary video drivers which
will need to change this setting back using the sysfs interfaces.

Signed-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: Make populate_rootfs asynchronous

The expansion of the initramfs is completely independant of other
boot activities.  The original data is already present at boot and the
filesystem is not required until we are ready to start init.  It is
therefore reasonable to populate the rootfs asynchronously.  Move this
processing to an async call.

This reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to
starting userspace) by several 10ths of a second on a selection of test
hardware particularly SMP systems, although UP system also benefit.

Signed-off-by: Surbhi Palande <surbhi.palande@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>

UBUNTU: SAUCE: isapnp_init: make isa PNP scans occur async

The results of scanning for devices is to trigger udev events therefore
we can push this processing async.

This reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to
starting userspace) by several 10ths of a second x86 32bit systems.

Signed-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>

payload.head: 8c067ff84850eaae1e9e67881b62c949c08e323a
shas:
On second thought, don't use 'enumerator' types in 'initiateStream'.

I could be wrong, but I don't think it's possible to get just the next
element from an enumerator, leaving it in a state where it can be
resumed. This means that the third argument of 'initiateStream' shouldn't
be an Enumerator.

It should be possible to just submit the next element to an iteratee,
but there is no guarantee that the resulting iteratee will be able to
consume more input. While we could retain the Iteratee types in the
last two arguments of 'intiateStream', I've decided not to.

Besides, now the data source and the header and data consumers can
simply be stored in the newly-created Stream. This should be enough
to get something that works; if the types turn out not to be ideal,
it should be relatively easy to change them later.

Since 'intiateStream' was the only thing that used Iteratee or Enumerator,
I've removed the dependency on the 'enumerator' package in the cabal file.

Rename 'ping.hs' to 'SPing.hs', and the module from 'Main' to 'SPing'.

Reading through the GHC flags, I see that with '-main-is' it is possible
to name the module containing the 'main' function. This will come in
handy when there is more than one little test program, since we won't
have several files containing 'Main' modules.

Implement just the basics of down-loading a data stream from the server.

This commit fills out enough of 'initiateStream', and adds enough
frame handlers in 'readFrames', that we can can open a half-open
stream in order to download the contents of a url from the 'flip'
server. I've tried this out and confirmed that it works with a small
test program, which I'll add in the next commit.

There is still a fair bit of stuff that is missing here. In particular:

- other than the first chunk of data, there is no way to submit further
  further data chunks to the remote endpoint

- if the list of headers is too big, we have no way to detect it, and
  have no way to continue the headers in additional HEADERS frames

- we do not respond to RST_STREAM frames, so if the server signals an
  error we will not properly clean up the stream

- we have no way to cancel open streams when there is a connection
  error, or when we receive a GOAWAY

- we do not defensively handle exceptions that can occur when calling
  into the application-supplied data source, header consumer, or
  data consumer

But, despite the short-comings, it seems we can correctly receive
SYN_REPLY and DATA frames.

In the process of making these changes, I realized that the proper
application-facing interface for 'initiateStream' should use the
client and the connection key. However, now there is an
inconsistency between 'ping' and 'initiateStream', in two respects:

- 'ping' puts the client and connection key arguments last, but
  'initiateStream' puts them first

- 'ping' collects all the ping-specific arguments in a value of type
  PingOptions, so there can be some reasonable defaults, but
  'initiateStream' does not. We should pick a style and stick with it.

I'll resolve these issues in future commits.

With respect to the issue of not sending all the data that might be
produced by the data-producer action, there isn't a lot of testing
that we can easily do here with the flip server -- or at least I don't
think there is. Maybe if we can arrange for some responses to HTTP
POSTS we can try the uploading functionality, but I'm not sure how
much we can really exercise it.

However, were we to start implementing a server, we could write some
unit tests that exercise the client and server talking to one
another. There is quite a bit of code that could be factored out into
a common 'EndPoint' module, so perhaps we should spend some time on
that. I've also noticed that it takes quite a while to download a
large file like '/usr/share/dict/words', so it would also be a good
idea to do a little profiling and see where the performance problem
lies.

Add SGet.hs, a small program for fetching a resource from the flip server.

SGet.hs is slightly more complicated than SPing, and downloads a resource
from the flip server. Currently, it prints the headers and data on stdout,
and logs all frames on stderr, so to make the output useful it's best
to separate the two streams with redirection, e.g.

 ./sget host port file > file 2> file.log

will put the output in <file> and the logged frames in <file.log>.

I've tried it out with a handful of files I've got loaded up in the
modified 'flip' server, including the contents of '/usr/share/dict/words'
on my system, and it can recover the data faithfully.

I've also added a Makefile that can build the 'sping' and 'sget' programs,
and I've updated '.gitignore' to ignore them and the temporary directory
used for the build output.

Produce a version of 'sget' with profiling enabled.

This adds a target for an 'sget-prof' binary for SGet, with GHC time and
space profiling enabled.

The profile for 'sget-prof' when transferring the 'words' file isn't
terribly elluminating; it says that almost all the time is spent in
'readFrames', which is to be expected. However, none of the functions
called by 'readFrames' appears to be an obvious culprit.

Using the unix 'time' program to time the execution of 'sget' for this
file indicates that more than half the time is spent doing system calls:

  $ time ./sget 127.0.0.1 10041 words > words 2> words.log

  real                      0m6.137s
  user                      0m2.540s
  sys                       0m3.572s

which suggests that block-buffering stdout and stderr might solve the
problem. I'll try that separately.

Block buffer 'stdout' and 'stderr' in SGet.

Block buffering 'stdout' and 'stderr' turns out to make a huge
difference. Here are a couple of runs of the 'time' command:

  $ time ./sget 127.0.0.1 10041 words > words 2> words.log

  real	0m0.218s
  user	0m0.072s
  sys	0m0.008s

  $ time ./sget 127.0.0.1 10041 words > words 2> words.log

  real	0m0.161s
  user	0m0.064s
  sys	0m0.020s

For comparison, that was taking well over 6 seconds before, so that's
a solid 25 times improvement.

Block-buffer 'stdout' and 'stderr' in SPing too.

It turns out that a lot of the time that we're measuring in SPing is
often the time to log frames to 'stderr'. Block-buffering 'stderr' and,
for good measure, 'stdout' improves the performance of SPing too. Now
many of the measured round-trip times round to zero milliseconds when
we're talking to the flip server on the loopback interface, which seems
reasonable.

Rearrange imports slightly in SPing.

Put the Network.SPDY imports last and in their own section, to be
consistent with the other modules.

Remove the unused 'receiveHeaders' and 'receiveData' functions in Client.

It turns out that these functions aren't really necessary, since it's
convenient and a bit more flexible to put the functionality in
'readFrames'. I've removed them.

Send WINDOW_UPDATE frames from the client.

SPDY flow control requires that the client send WINDOW_UPDATE frames
when it consumes data sent by the server and frees up buffer space.
Once a DATA frame arrives with the FIN flag set, the client sends no
further WINDOW_UPDATE frames.

Since the client immediately passes received data chunks to the
data consumer associated with the stream, we need to change the type
of the consumer so it tells the client how much buffer space is
released. The consumer now has the type

  Maybe ByteString -> IO DeltaWindowSize

so it can say how many bytes have been released each time it is fed
more data.

It's possible that in some circumstances the application may take a
while to release buffer space, and so this interface may not be
sufficient. We should really add a function to the API specifically
for reporting changes in the window size when the data consumer
doesn't report window size changes. However, for many circumstances,
this interface may be enough. I'll make a separate commit to add
another API function.

These changes required a modest compensating change in the SGet test
program. There, the data consumer immediately writes bytes out to
stdout, so it always reports that the entire byte string is consumed.

The 'flip' server does not implement flow control, and in fact it has
absolutely no response to WINDOW_UPDATE frames. I've modified my version
of the server so that it logs WINDOW_UPDATE frames, but I currently
have no third-party server against which I can test my understanding of
flow control. That may need to wait until we can use TLS + NPN.

Derive Integral and supporting type class instances for DeltaWindowSize.

It will be convenient if DeltaWindowSize is an instance of Integral.
I've derived the default instance of Integral, and of the required
super classes.

This change enables some minor simplifications in the SGet test program,
which I've included here.

Don't send WINDOW_UPDATE frames if there is no change in window size.

It's entirely possible that the data consumer for a stream will report
a zero change in the window size. When this happens, there is no point
in sending a WINDOW_UPDATE frame to the sending endpoint. It's probably
harmless to do so, but why incur an unnecessary flush on the outgoing
network connection? I've guarded against this in 'readFrames'.

Add a public 'updateWindow' API function to the Client module.

There is a chance that application code will need to explicitly
participate in the SPDY flow control by signalling when there is
extra space in the window for data received from the remote endpoint.
I've added an 'updateWindow' function to do this, and factored out
the common code between it and 'readFrames' into "updateWindow'".

This isn't used yet, but I think it is necessary in the API.

Add a StreamOptions type and use it in 'initiateStream'.

The signature of 'initiateStream' is very long, and there may well be
some other arguments we'll need to add in the future. It is also
inconsistent with the signature for 'ping', which collects the ping-
specific arguments in a PingOptions type. So it seems reasonable to
add a StreamOptions type and a default 'defaultStreamOptions' value.

The 'defaultStreamOptions' value lets us get rid of 'defaultPriority',
and use simply Priority instead of (Maybe Priority) without burdening
application code. I've made the necessary adjustments in the SGet
module, and confirmed that I can still download files from the flip
server.

I've kept the list of headers out of StreamOptions, since the only
essential argument when creating a stream is the list of initial
headers for inclusion in the SYN_STREAM frame.

There is still one minor inconsistency between 'ping' and
'initiateStream'.  In 'ping', the client and connection key arguments
come after the options, whereas in 'initiateStream' they come before
the headers and options.  I'll pick one style in a subsequent commit.

Improve some of the API comments regarding flow control.

I've moved around and reworded some documentation so that it's a bit
clearer what the DeltaWindowSize is for in 'streamOptsDataConsumer'
and 'windowUpdate'. I'm still not very satisfied with it, but it will
do for now.

Add some notes on common behaviours of clients and servers.

A lot of the code in the Client module could be moved into a common
'EndPoint' module, and then be specialized for building a Client and
a Server. I've jotted down a few notes on what I think is needed to
allow extracting the common code.

The most pressing thing I think is to change the frame types so we
can deal with different kinds of frames as different types. This
can make it easier to plug in responses for different kinds of frames
that must be treated a bit differently by clients and servers, and
also make it impossible to accidentally use the wrong field selector
with the wrong variant of a multi-variant type.

That rework isn't difficult, but it will be messy, so I will perform
it in several small commits, starting next.

Move the DataFrame fields into a Data type.

This is the first step in a large reworking of the frame types, aimed
at allowing client and server code to treat individual frames in a
more abstract way. It will also make it impossible to use a field
selector for one variant of frame with another.

The unit tests still pass, and the test programs still build and work.

Move the SynStream fields into a separate SynStream type.

This is step 2 in the big frame type refactoring, and is the first of
the control frames. The tests still pass and the test programs still
run.

Move the SynReply fields into a SynReply type.

Step 3 in the big refactoring. The tests still pass and the test
programs still build and run.

Move the RstStream fields into an RstStream type.

Part 4 of the big refactoring. The tests still pass and the test programs
still compile and run.

in current code,

```
def add_http_status_to_jsonp_response
  @add_http_status_to_jsonp_response || true
end
```
this function returns true if `@add_http_status_to_jsonp_response` be false.

so, I wrote quick fix for around this issue.

shas: Report errors thrown from uncaughtException handers
Implicitly add EventEmitters to active domain
Implicitly add timers to active domain
domain: add members, remove ctor cb
Don't hijack bound callbacks for Domain error events
A test of multiple domains in process at once
Put the active domain on the process object
Only intercept error arg if explicitly requested

Don't auto-add new domains to the current domain

While an automatic parent/child relationship is sort of neat,
and leads to some nice error-bubbling characteristics, it also
results in keeping a reference to every EE and timer created,
unless domains are explicitly disposed of.

Explicitly adding one domain to another is still fine, of course.
Disposing of a domain removes it from its parent
Domain disposal turns functions into no-ops
An example using domains in an HTTP server

Recover lost tables used for incoming email -- this is ~ the original code, so mods needed to make it current will be visible. Inbox table was last seen in Launchpad revision 719, June 2010. Status table persisted until the file was moved to modules. This should be integrated w/ generic inbound messaging.

Adjust inbound email code so it runs and stores email in the original inbox table. Does not yet call receive_msg or use msg_log.

In run_scheduler_tasks, show trace for failed task. (Sorry, not related to inbound email.)

Deprecate cron version of email reader as it's been moved to scheduler.

Since no-one is using inbound email yet, take this opportunity to change table names, etc., to indicate they're for inbound email.

Allow scheduling fetches from different email sources independently, e.g. so they can be fetched at different intervals. Since the scheduler would try to run it, comment out the example of scheduling a task.

pull_request.title: Created new FieldContext for annotation handlers processing fields
pull_request.body:
Hey Lincoln,

I'm currently finishing the implementation of some of the annotation handlers. During working on this I noticed that it would make sense to have some kind of field context object that is able to hold information that affects only the field currently processed by the handlers. IMHO this makes sense because the annotations placed on a single field typically process some "entity" (like a binding for example) and therefore need to share some information.

This pull request contains a new context called `FieldContext` which extends `ClassContext`. This context currently only provides the possibility to register a "current binding" (`@ParameterBinding` does this) and to retrieve it (which other handles could to to enrich the binding).

I already modified two of the annotation handlers to use this new field context. The `ParameterBindingHandler` registers the just created binding:

https://github.com/chkal/prettyfaces/blob/field-context/annotations/src/main/java/org/ocpsoft/prettyfaces/annotation/handlers/ParameterBindingHandler.java#L93

And the `JSFValidatorHandler` retrieves this binding to attach a validator:

https://github.com/chkal/prettyfaces/blob/field-context/annotations/src/main/java/org/ocpsoft/prettyfaces/annotation/handlers/JSFValidatorHandler.java#L44

Works fine! :)

What do you think?

shas: added src files - not much there yet though
mostly comments documenting pin and matrix assignment
worked on pin assignments a little; and some other minor updates
split the firmware into general/controller/keyboard files

still working...

  chips reset on powerup
- the partitioning of code into files is all wrong at the moment... i
  need to write some more and then fix that
mostly: figured out how to initialize the LEDs with PWM
working more on controller_init(), and file factoring

*lots* of stuff .. :) - got PWM working!

also, i didn't make a note of it in the *.md file, but Waveform
Generation Mode 15 for fast PWM wasn't working right (well.. wasn't
working how i expected it to).  i misinterpreted what the modes were
doing, partially (haha, or all-ly?) because i didn't read the
description of fast pwm thoroughly enough...  in any case, all the
information's in the datasheet, and it's actually not terribly long.
i'm not sure how to correctly use Mode 15 yet, but i think i'll leave it
alone for now, since Mode 5 works as expected, and i think what the
datasheet says about *that* makes enough sense to me for me to be
content for the moment.

doing something clever with macro prefixes, which didn't work

i'd like to keep it around in the history though, just for fun - :)
intermitent checkin; lots of stuff; i2c on hold; kb logic in progress
little work on the teensy init function and header; not much else

few things; mostly, I2C works now!; it was a hardware error

i had been leaving the RESET pin floating... this does not work.  it
must be externally biased - high, if you want the chip to work.. :) lol

mostly working on mcp23018.c; init() and update() might be ready :)

also, moved the twi code to lib/teensy-2-0/twi*

lots

- fixed some includes (`uint8_t` comes from a header, not the language)
- put code from some of the .h files into .c files
- now using open drain logic (hi-Z or GND) on both chips instead of
  driving the row pins high on the teensy, or using a pull-up resistor
  on the row pins with the mcp23018
- put `return 0;` at the end of some functions that weren't void
- fixed/updated some documentation; esp. the row assignments for the
  mcp23018
- generalized the unused/row/column pin assignment and init code using
  macros, so they'll be much easier to move around if necessary
- fixed a redefinition error in "lib/usb/keyboard-usage-page.h"
wrote teensy update() (need to test); minor mcp23018 update() fix
(forgot to add these to git the other day)

lots and lots; now writing/debugging keyboard logic

also, mcp23018_init() needs fixing: `twi_stop()` needs to be at the end
of transmission blocks.  i wouldn't think that would be necessary, but
it seems to be the only thing that'll make it work, and it also seems
consistent with the protocol diagram in the datasheet (lol, imagine
that), so i think that's what i'll have to do.  not as though it matters
much i guess, since it's a single master / single slave system anyway, i
was just hoping not to release the bus till i was finished..

checkin before deleting the debug code; almost ready for first beta!

- simple bug fix in kbfun_press() and kbfun_release()
- no longer check for previous init() in the mcp23018 functions;
  something would happen when i tried to read from it, sometimes, when
  it'd been unplugged or stoped some other way, and it would hang - and
  the only thing that would make it better was running the test_twi_2
  function (a series of writes, with stops after each).  so now
  mcp23018_init() is a series of writes, with stops after each.  it
  doesn't take appreciably longer to run...  maybe it should be looked
  into later though.
- changed the main() loop a little
added ergodox circuit diagram; and a few misc things; time to clean up

payload.head: ff34d401ff385ef7173ca612432b4ea717fff690
shas:
Implement support for 18 of the GNU-compatible __atomic builtins.

This is not quite sufficient for libstdc++'s <atomic>: we still need
__atomic_test_and_set and __atomic_clear, and may need a more complete
__atomic_is_lock_free implementation.

We are also missing an implementation of __atomic_always_lock_free,
__atomic_nand_fetch, and __atomic_fetch_nand, but those aren't needed
for libstdc++.

payload.head: 32b6dfca13e4fbbb4871aba93c296137a59fce37
shas:
asfdec: Add an option for not searching for the packet markers

Some streams don't contain these.

Signed-off-by: Martin Storsjö <martin@martin.st>

rtpdec_asf: Set the no_resync_search option for the chained asf demuxer

Searching for packet markers doesn't make sense for this use case,
where packets are fed one at a time to the demuxer.

This fixes playing back streams that have packets not starting
with the 0x82, 0x00, 0x00 marker.

Signed-off-by: Martin Storsjö <martin@martin.st>

fate: try to fix >8bit dpx reg test

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

mpegpsenc: fix user specified mux rate

Fixes Ticket1175

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

put_bits: switch assert to av_assert2()

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

build system: support setting avassert() assert_level

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

adpcmenc: fix encoded s_0 value.

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

proresenc_anatoly: fix encoded mantissa.

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

proresenc_kostya: fix encoded mantissa.

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

proresenc_kostya: Mention likely ancestry in the license header.

As the encoder contained the same bug and has similar structure
to anatoliys encoder, it is possibly based on it.

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

aacenc: Fix issues with huge values of bit_rate.

Do not pointlessly call ff_alloc_packet2 multiple times,
and fix an infinite loop by clamping the maximum
number of bits to target in the algorithm that does
not use lambda.

Signed-off-by: Reimar Döffinger <Reimar.Doeffinger@gmx.de>

Add tests for audio encoders: aac, dca, ra144 and nellymoser.

The PSNR values are of varying usefulness, though at least
the DTS and AAC ones are useful with the right shift value.
Note: due to usage of floats some of these may fail on other
architectures.
In that case they should be converted into a CMD = stddev
FATE test, but it seems useful to try this way first.

Signed-off-by: Reimar Döffinger <Reimar.Doeffinger@gmx.de>

Remove AAC and nellymoser tests that do not work.

Signed-off-by: Reimar Döffinger <Reimar.Doeffinger@gmx.de>

Add AAC FATE encode tests.

Signed-off-by: Reimar Döffinger <Reimar.Doeffinger@gmx.de>

fate: try to force le for the dpx decoder side too

Signed-off-by: Michael Niedermayer <michaelni@gmx.at>

lavfi: port libmpcodecs remove-logo filter

The code is based on the remove-logo filter in MPlayer/libmpcodecs, by
Robert Edele, relicensed to LGPL with consent of the author.

Address trac issue #249.

lavfi/mp: remove remove_logo wrapper

removelogo has been ported to libavfilter, and the wrapper was not
working.
doc/filters: remove reference to removed delogo wrapper

doc/muxers: update documentation for the framecrc muxer

Add mention to the pts and duration log fields, added in
d2afbd9a56e4e863bad01923006dd9b77f747035.

Fix trac ticket #1159.

doc/muxers: clarify documentation for the framecrc muxer

Makes more explicit that framecrc works at the packet level, also prefers
the term "packet" over "frame" when it makes sense.
